As I read from the wikipedia page of the linking number, it says that the linking number of two curves $\gamma_1$ and $\gamma_2$ in space can be found using the integral 
$$\,\frac{1}{4\pi}
\oint_{\gamma_1}\oint_{\gamma_2}
\frac{\mathbf{r}_1 - \mathbf{r}_2}{|\mathbf{r}_1 - \mathbf{r}_2|^3}
\cdot (d\mathbf{r}_1 \times d\mathbf{r}_2)$$
It says the integrand is the Jacobian of the Gaussian map
$$\Gamma(s,t) = \frac{\gamma_1(s) - \gamma_2(t)}{|\gamma_1(s) - \gamma_2(t)|}$$
Following Ted's comment I am able to show that $$\oint_{\gamma_1}\oint_{\gamma_2}
\left\|\frac{\partial\Gamma}{\partial s}\times \frac{\partial\Gamma}{\partial t}\right\|\,dsdt = 
\oint_{\gamma_1}\oint_{\gamma_2}
\frac{1}{|\mathbf{r}_1 - \mathbf{r}_2|^3}
\left|
(\mathbf{r}_1 - \mathbf{r}_2)\cdot \left (\frac{d\mathbf{r}_1}{ds} \times \frac{d\mathbf{r}_2}{dt}\right)\right| ds dt$$
